All social revolution are decided by whether or not the military goes over to the side of the people. That being said, when speaking of "the military" there are those who give orders and create policy, and those who have been conditioned to follow orders. The former are the enemies of a people seeking freedom from military dictatorship, the latter are, when the revolution moment strikes, often not (but not always). A people are almost always better off solving their own nation's problems, but this is very difficult in a military dictatorship. Military interventions almost always lead to unnecessary bloodshed, oppression, and exploitation. 

Make sure you are using Tor (with bridges/ pluggable transports) to access ZeroNet). I cannot speak to the specifics of your situation, only what I have learned from history. Solidarity.

@Realjohndoe Russia is an imperialist country just like the United States. Your analysis of the middle east is a bit nuanced. In the 1960's, Afghanistan for instance was one of the most progressive liberal democracies in the world (long after the founding of Israel). The Soviet and American led interventions in the area after a failed revolution sparked a reaction that ripples to this day. They used to joke about making women cover themselves, then they did. The state of Israel had nothing to do with this. I am opposed to the occupation of Palestine, but I strongly sense your opposition to the excesses of the state of Israel stem not from concern for the oppression of the Palestinians, but from antisemitism and race hatred. The ((())) brackets denote antisemitism, but I am sure you already know this. Regardless, such fascistic symbolism is deplorable. In Rojava the Kurdish people are building a stateless democracy in the Middle East and it is actually working quite well.

@klu9@zeroid.bit: I personally am completely opposed to state ownership. I see the state as something as intrinsically evil as a private corporation. You can say it's "property of the whole people" but we know from history how undemocratic state ownership works, and for something like Facebook it would harm civil liberty, not help it. Would state ownership be better with a more genuine democracy? A socialist democracy? Maybe, but I would prefer not to, especially in regards to the US government.

Marxian economist Richard Wolff proposes Workers Self-Directed Enterprises (WSDE's) in his book "Democracy At Work: A Cure For Capitalism". I think this is a good starting point. Board members and the people who run the company would be democratically elected by the workers themselves, instantly recallable at all times and responsible to the people, and perhaps for a big company with representation to the general public. That would also mean that such representatives would likely not be paid much more than the average worker, who is going to elect someone who wants to give themselves a million dollar salary?

As to the specific forms such a thing would take? I would say you can certainly decree that private ownership be abolished, but what to come in its place? I can say yes, democracy, but as to specifics that lies in the mists of the future. Ultimately the forms such a thing would take would have to be up to the people themselves to figure out on their own. I personally advocate something along the lines of WSDE's as Wolff advocates with more public representation, a bit different from a co-op and very different from state ownership. I see market socialism at the very least as a necessary evil, perhaps a catalyst for something grander? Only time will tell.

@Petrina: Thanks for the question! I assume you mean updating the mirrors so I will answer that (correct me if I am wrong). 

It's actually somewhat of a process when I make a post. I usually publish first on redliberty.org using a WordPress Whonix VM (Tor). Then I preview the post and copy the relevant aspects of the page source to paste it into the index.html file in my Freenet VM and I insert it into Freenet. Then I copy the index.html file into my ZeroNet VM where I then sign and publish the site to update it. Then I put that index.html onto a flash drive and physically pop it into my I2P server where I use VNC to copy the index.html file into the docroot of my redliberty.i2p eepsite. Then I pop the flash drive into my Tor server and repeat the process on there. I also update my Sone on Freenet and my ZeroMe (where you are) alerting the world to the new post.

Usually this takes me about 30 minutes to an hour for each post. It's actually quite frustrating at times and sometimes I get annoyed but ultimately I think it's for the greater good and that's what keeps making me do it over and over again every time I publish a post. I mean, I'm adding good content to censorship resistant networks and meeting cool people at the same time so why not? Is anyone afraid of ending up on a list for visiting a socialist blog? Not on Tor/I2P/Freenet/ZeroNet they aren't! Not to mention the fact that some people in authoritarian/unstable countries might actually benefit from being able to read my writings here. In the future I plan to simplify/ automate this whole process but for now I gotta do what I gotta do. It's a lot of virtual machines, flash drives, and VNC connections but whatever gets the job done right?

@Brianhanson2nd: Here I must quote Emma Goldman as I say that I do not hate the people of any nation, only the crimes committed by the states that rule over them. You do know that socialist politics originate from the radical labor movement right? That their goal is the emancipation of labor (working people/ common citizens such as yourself) from both capital and the state right?

Goldman:

"Thinking men and women the world over are beginning to realize that patriotism is too narrow and limited a conception to meet the necessities of our time. The centralization of power has brought into being an international feeling of solidarity among the oppressed nations of the world; a solidarity which represents a greater harmony of interests between the workingman of America and his brothers abroad than between the American miner and his exploiting compatriot; a solidarity which fears not foreign invasion, because it is bringing all the workers to the point when they will say to their masters, 'Go and do your own killing. We have done it long enough for you.'"
